# Implementation Summary

## What Was Built

A Python evaluation pipeline implementing the LLM-as-judge cascade designed in Part 1,
applied to Prompt #3 (hallucinated medication detection) of the custom discharge letter
evaluation. The pipeline runs five simulated model outputs through a three-step
verification cascade: a completeness gate (Step 0) confirming all three required
medications are present, a dosage tuple check (Step 0b) verifying correct mg values via
regex, and a whitelist check (Step 1) flagging any drug names outside the permitted list.
Only terms that survive to Step 1 as flags are escalated to the LLM judge (gpt-4o-mini,
temperature=0), which classifies each flagged term as HALLUCINATION, PARAPHRASE, or
GENERALIZATION using a structured few-shot prompt with explicit reasoning steps. All
results — per-case outcomes, judge reasoning, token usage, latency, and cost — are saved
to evaluation_results.json.

## Key Findings

The cascade correctly classified all five test cases with 100% accuracy against expected
outcomes. Two hallucinations were detected (Metformin, Trap 1; Cefazolin, Trap 3), both
classified as HALLUCINATION with HIGH confidence by the judge. One distortion was caught
rule-based at Step 0b (Enoxaparin 80mg instead of 40mg) without any judge call. The
LMWH paraphrase passed correctly through the whitelist without escalation. Critically,
only 2 of 5 cases required a judge call — the cascade successfully kept API usage
minimal, with a total cost of $0.000536 USD for the full run. This confirms the
cost-efficiency argument for the cascade design: rule-based checks handle clear cases
cheaply, the judge is reserved for genuine ambiguity.

## Limitations and Next Steps

The test cases are manually constructed and represent best-case conditions — each failure
mode is deliberately isolated and unambiguous. In production, model outputs will contain
overlapping issues (e.g., simultaneous omission and hallucination) and edge cases the
whitelist does not cover. The whitelist-based drug extraction is also brittle: it relies
on capitalization patterns and a fixed stopword list, which will produce false positives
or missed flags on unusual formatting. A production implementation would require a
dedicated NER (named entity recognition) step for drug name extraction. Additionally,
each prompt was evaluated once at temperature=0 — multiple runs per case are needed to
measure output variance and report results as mean and standard deviation rather than
single-point estimates.